					3.6 The&nbsp;Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Representation Theorem &nbsp;
					In this section, we brieﬂy discuss a famous representation theorem initially due &nbsp;
					to Riesz in the case of functions deﬁned on the unit interval. This theorem is a &nbsp;
					cornerstone of the functional-analytic approach to measure theory. We say little &nbsp;
					about this approach in the present book, because the “abstract” approach that we &nbsp;
					have presented is much more adapted to applications to probability theory. &nbsp;
					Recall that a topological space X is called locally compact if every point of X &nbsp;
					has a compact neighborhood. Let us consider a locally compact metric space X. The &nbsp;
					vector space of all real continuous functions with compact support on X is denoted &nbsp;
					by Cc(X). A linear form J on Cc(X) is a linear mapping from Cc(X) into R. It is &nbsp;
					said to be positive if J(f ) ≥ 0 whenever f ≥ 0. &nbsp;
					A Radon measure on X is a measure μ on (X, B(X)) such that μ(K) &lt; ∞ for &nbsp;
					every compact subset K of X. If μ is a Radon measure on X, the formula &nbsp;
					ꢉ
					J(f ) = f dμ &nbsp;









